054724,"guid":"D72631909208453894F3D4D11C4D6871","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">Preoperative Care<\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><span>1. All animals <\/span><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">must be<\/span><span> singly-housed, given Ensure 12 hours before surgery and have all bedding removed. <\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\">2. Preoperative pain medications should be administered: <\/div><div class = \"text-block\">    a. Ketoprofen (5 mg\/kg) <\/div><div class = \"text-block\">    b. Saline is given at the end of surgery and a second dose is given 24 hours later. <\/div><div class = \"text-block\">3. Ensure adequacy of anesthesia. <\/div><div class = \"text-block\">4. Place mouse on surgical board\/surgical field over a warm water circulating blanket and immobilize gently. <\/div><div class = \"text-block\">5. Prep and drape animal sterilely. <\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":null,"data":null,"section":null,"section_color":null,"duration":0},{"id":722704,"guid":"E95353F04A6711E99DD68D65A4DD5C11","previous_id":722701,"previous_guid":"6D6E1A904A6711E99DD68D65A4DD5C11","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"555D7E5D32E0408EBA7EC725E2D5DF97","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":""}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"709CBD6EF4914C81BF817E8A782CED6A","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">Operation<\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\">1. Begin the procedure by making a midline laparotomy incision with sharp surgical scissors. Be sure to stay on the linea alba and away from the rectus abdominus muscles. <\/div><div class = \"text-block\">2. Using cotton swabs, gently sweep the intestinal contents until the stomach is located. <\/div><div class = \"text-block\">3. Ligate the stomach at the level of the pylorus with a 6-0 silk suture to impede flow, but not to strangulate the tissue. <\/div><div class = \"text-block\">4. Identify a portion of jejunum approximately 4cm distal to the Ligament of Treitz and transect this bowel using 8-0 nylon suture. Divide the mesentery as necessary to allow for sufficient mobilization of the bowel to prevent torsion. <\/div><div class = \"text-block\">5. Close the proximal and distal ends of small bowel with 8-0 nylon suture. <\/div><div class = \"text-block\">6. Next, measure out 12cm distally from the distal sutured end of the small bowel. <\/div><div class = \"text-block\">7. With extreme care, on the proximal end of the small bowel limb create a running-continuous, side to side gastroenterostomy that is at least 1.5cm in length on the anterior surface of the stomach just proximal to the greater curvature using 7-0 PDS II. <\/div><div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/pr-journal\/beqca.jpg\" \/><\/div><div class = \"text-block\">8. Place ligatures on all stomach or mesenteric vessels using 7-0 PDS II as needed for hemostasis, though take caution not to disrupt the blood supply to the anastomosis. <\/div><div class = \"text-block\">9. Once the proximal end of the procedure is completed and hemostasis adequate, create a side to side enteroenterostomy between the native jejunum and the gastric limb of the transposed bowel. <\/div><div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/pr-journal\/beqda.jpg\" \/><\/div><div class = \"text-block\">This will restore continuity of the biliopancreatic secretions with alimentary flow. <\/div><div class = \"text-block\">10. As necessary, irrigate the abdominal cavity to wash away any small bowel contamination or blood clots. <\/div><div class = \"text-block\">11. Finally, close the abdomen in a simple, two-layer, interrupted fashion. The first interrupted layer should be a simple, interrupted muscle layer with 6-0 monocryl suture. Using good technique suture the connective tissue and not the muscle proper. The second layer is a skin layer also done in a simple, interrupted fashion with 7-0 Prolene suture. <\/div><\/div>"}},{"id":1054725,"guid":"0D701F48FACF49A8A5198073C62C454F","order_id":2,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/pr-journal\/beqca.jpg\" \/><\/div>"}},{"id":1054726,"guid":"35AA15A2941A40349E697DC56726BC33","order_id":3,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/pr-journal\/beqda.jpg\" \/><\/div>"}}],"cases":null,"data":null,"section":null,"section_color":null,"duration":0},{"id":722707,"guid":"67F319704A6811E99DD68D65A4DD5C11","previous_id":722704,"previous_guid":"E95353F04A6711E99DD68D65A4DD5C11","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"4E2BA35DCA3E43EC8F31CB9C7146820B","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":""}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"52E8FD24C011455B8623EA05870BE8BF","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">Postoperative Care <\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\">1. All mice receive 1.0 ml of warmed, sterile saline following the procedure before being placed in the recovery cages. <\/div><div class = \"text-block\">2. All mouse cages are kept partially on a veterinary-approved heating pad for 5 to 7 days postoperatively. <\/div><div class = \"text-block\">3. Mice will remain on an Ensure diet for 24 hours post-surgery no bedding in the cage. <\/div><div class = \"text-block\">4. Mice are monitored until recovered from the procedure, which typically takes 7-14 days depending on the procedure. General behavior (i.e. bright\/alert\/responsive vs. depressed\/obtunded) is monitored. <\/div><div class = \"text-block\">5. Pain medication is administered per protocol: ketoprofen 5 mg\/kg post-op and again at 24 hours postoperative. <\/div><div class = \"text-block\">6. Additional pain medication may be needed depending on postoperative recovery. <\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":null,"data":null,"section":null,"section_color":null,"duration":0}],"materials":[{"id":182161,"mol_weight":0,"name":"6-0 monocryl suture ","linfor":null,"url":"https:\/\/www.ethicon.com\/na\/epc\/code\/y432h?lang=en-default","sku":"Y432H","cas_number":"","rrid":"","public":0,"vendor":{"name":"Ethicon","affiliation":null,"username":null,"link":"https:\/\/www.ethicon.com\/","image":{"source":"https:\/\/www.protocols.io\/img\/vendors\/placeholder.png","placeholder":"https:\/\/www.protocols.io\/img\/vendors\/placeholder.png"},"badges":[],"research_interests":null,"id":645},"can_edit":0,"stats":{"total_protocols":0}},{"id":182162,"mol_weight":0,"name":"7-0 prolene","linfor":null,"url":"https:\/\/www.ethicon.com\/na\/epc\/code\/8648g?lang=en-default","sku":"8648G","cas_number":"","rrid":"","public":0,"vendor":{"name":"Ethicon","affiliation":null,"username":null,"link":"https:\/\/www.ethicon.com\/","image":{"source":"https:\/\/www.protocols.io\/img\/vendors\/placeholder.png","placeholder":"https:\/\/www.protocols.io\/img\/vendors\/placeholder.png"},"badges":[],"research_interests":null,"id":645},"can_edit":0,"stats":{"total_protocols":0}},{"id":182163,"mol_weight":0,"name":"7-0 PDS II ","linfor":null,"url":"https:\/\/www.ethicon.com\/na\/epc\/search\/keyword\/7-0%20PDS%20II?lang=en-default","sku":"H206Z1551R","cas_number":"","rrid":"","public":0,"vendor":{"name":"Ethicon","affiliation":null,"username":null,"link":"https:\/\/www.ethicon.com\/","image":{"source":"https:\/\/www.protocols.io\/img\/vendors\/placeholder.png","placeholder":"https:\/\/www.protocols.io\/img\/vendors\/placeholder.png"},"badges":[